udies Association Journal "Grab your copy at your local bookseller and get hip to what your hair is saying to others with regards to beauty, culture and politics. Learn about how culture has a love for coifs, because after all, so do you!"-Sophisticate's Black Hair Styles Guide Drawing on interviews with over 50 women, from teens to seniors, Hair Matters is the first book on the politics of Black hair to be based on substantive, ethnographically informed research. Focusing on the everyday discussions that Black women have among themselves and about themselves, Ingrid Banks analyzes how talking about hair reveals Black women's ideas about race, gender, sexuality, beauty, and power. Ultimately, what emerges is a survey of Black women's consciousness within both their own communities and mainstream culture at large.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAfrican American womenvInterviews. 0aAfrican American womenxInterviews. 0aAfrican American womenxRace identity. 0aAfrican American womenxSocial conditions. 0aAfrican American womenxSocial life and customs. 0aBeauty, PersonalxSocial aspectsxUnited States. 0aBeauty, PersonalxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aHairxSocial aspectsxUnited States. 0aHairxSocial aspectszUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / African American Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z97831107064440 cprintz978081471336540uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9780814739457.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814739457423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780814739457/original  a978-3-11-070644-4  New York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EE